04394nam a22006855i 9780292721487DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927214877 a10.7560/191632doi  a(DE-B1597)587372  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aARC0050002bisacsh04a711.5509722231 aWagner, Logan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAncient Origins of the Mexican Plaza :bFrom Primordial Sea to Public Space /cLogan Wagner, Susan Kline Morehead, Hal Box. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthors’ Note -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One The Primordial Sea Forming Open Space in Mesoamerica -- tChapter Two Forming Spanish Towns in Mesoamerican Culture -- tChapter Three Sixteenth-Century Communal Open Spaces (Five Hundred Years Later) -- tChapter Four Origins and Evolution -- tEpilogue Plazas in the Twenty-First Century -- tAppendix Measured Drawings: Plans of Towns -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe plaza has been a defining feature of Mexican urban architecture and culture for at least 4,000 years. Ancient Mesoamericans conducted most of their communal life in outdoor public spaces, and today the plaza is still the public living room in every Mexican neighborhood, town, and city—the place where friends meet, news is shared, and personal and communal rituals and celebrations happen. The site of a community’s most important architecture—church, government buildings, and marketplace—the plaza is both sacred and secular space and thus the very heart of the community. This extensively illustrated book traces the evolution of the Mexican plaza from Mesoamerican sacred space to modern public gathering place. The authors led teams of volunteers who measured and documented nearly one hundred traditional Mexican town centers. The resulting plans reveal the layers of Mesoamerican and European history that underlie the contemporary plaza. The authors describe how Mesoamericans designed their ceremonial centers as embodiments of creation myths—the plaza as the primordial sea from which the earth emerged. They discuss how Europeans, even though they sought to eradicate native culture, actually preserved it as they overlaid the Mesoamerican sacred plaza with the Renaissance urban concept of an orthogonal grid with a central open space. The authors also show how the plaza’s historic, architectural, social, and economic qualities can contribute to mainstream urban design and architecture today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArchitecture and societyzMexicoxHistory. 0aPlazaszMexicoxHistory. 0aPublic spaceszMexicoxHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBox, Hal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMorehead, Susan Kline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292721487423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292721487/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK